This is likely the Harlem River Speedway, which opened July 2, 1898, in New York City for light harness horse pleasure competitions.[<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F70F12FA3A5D11738DDDAA0894DF405B8885F0D3" rel="nofollow">1</a>] &nbsp; &quot;The Speedway&quot;, as it was known, served as a racecourse until 1915, after which it eventually became the Harlem River Drive, and today features a bicycle path along the river side. [<a href="http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/M141/highlights/8260" rel="nofollow">2</a>]

Nathan Straus, who co-owned two of New York City's biggest department stores – R.H. Macy &amp; Company and Abraham &amp; Straus[<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathan_Straus" rel="nofollow">3</a>], was the owner of a grey trotting gelding named &quot;Denver&quot;.  Denver held a notable record of accomplishments on The Speedway (2:11&frac14;), and was frequently reported on by <i>The New York Times</i> during the Fall of 1910 (known as the &quot;Fall Brushing Season&quot;). [<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F60C12F7395D11738DDDAE0994D8415B808DF1D3" rel="nofollow">4</a>] [<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F00B1EFC345D16738DDDAF0A94D1405B808DF1D3" rel="nofollow">5</a>] [<a href="http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F50E16F93A5813738DDDAE0894D9415B838DF1D3" rel="nofollow">6</a>]
